## 7. ⚡ Performance Issues Report

### PERF-001 🔴 HIGH — 3,713-Line Monolithic Backend File

**File:** `server/src/index.ts`

The entire backend (80+ routes, 3 helper functions, multer config, CORS config) lives in a single file. This creates:
- Slow startup due to single large module parse
- Impossible to unit test individual route handlers
- Merge conflicts in team development
- No separation of concerns

**Fix:** Split into route modules:
```
server/src/
├── index.ts          (app setup, middleware, listen)
├── routes/
│   ├── auth.ts
│   ├── employees.ts
│   ├── inquiries.ts
│   ├── selections.ts
│   ├── calculations.ts
│   ├── quotations.ts
│   ├── catalogs.ts
│   ├── attendance.ts
│   ├── pipeline.ts
│   └── architects.ts
├── middleware/
│   └── authMiddleware.ts
└── helpers/
    └── logActivity.ts
```

---

### PERF-002 🟡 MEDIUM — No Pagination Causes N+1 and Memory Issues

See DB-004 above. Additionally, `/api/products/all` (line 550) returns **all products from all catalogs** without any limit — this will become a serious performance issue as catalog data grows.

---

### PERF-003 🟡 MEDIUM — N+1 Query in Local Calculation Save

**File:** `server/src/index.ts`  
**Lines:** 2200–2209

```typescript
for (const item of items) {
  await prisma.selectionItem.update({ ... }); // Sequential DB calls in a loop
}
```

Each item triggers a separate DB round-trip. With 20 items, this is 20 sequential queries.

**Fix:**
```typescript
// Use Promise.all for parallel execution
await Promise.all(items.map(item =>
  prisma.selectionItem.update({ where: { id: item.selectionItemId }, data: { ... } })
));
```

---

### PERF-004 🟢 LOW — `@supabase/supabase-js` Inflates Bundle

Already reported in FE-001. Removing this library could reduce the JS bundle by ~200KB.

---

### PERF-005 🟢 LOW — Large Frontend Pages Without Code Splitting

**Files:** `src/pages/Catalogs/Catalogs.tsx` (75KB), `src/pages/piplines/Pipeline.tsx` (66KB), `src/pages/Attendance/Attendance.tsx` (43KB)

These are very large single-file React components. Without lazy loading, they all load at once on first page visit.

**Fix:** Use `React.lazy()` and `Suspense` in `App.tsx`:
```typescript
const Catalogs = React.lazy(() => import('./pages/Catalogs/Catalogs'));
```

---

